{{ill|Takakurayama (Ise)|ja|高倉山|12=draft|12=draft}} (たかくらやま) is a collective name for the mountainous area within the precincts of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}'s {{ill|Gekū (Ise Grand Shrine)|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, located in {{ill|Ise, Mie|ja|伊勢市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Overview == {{right|[[File:Takakura-yama(Ise)_02.JPG|thumb|256px|Distant view of Takakurayama]]}} Takakurayama is a general term for the mountainous area surrounding '''{{ill|Gekū (Ise Grand Shrine)|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}''', consisting of '''Takasayama''', '''Hiwashiyama (日鷲山)''', '''Karisaka-mine (賀利佐我峰)''', '''Sanukiyama (佐貫山)''', and '''Otonashiyama (音無山)'''.
However, the '''highest peak is Hiwashiyama, standing at 117 meters''' ({{coord|34|28|55|N|136|41|57|E|region:JP|display=inline}}), which is '''commonly referred to as Takakurayama'''. On maps by the '''{{ill|Geospatial Information Authority of Japan|ja|国土地理院|12=draft|12=draft}}''', the peak of Hiwashiyama is labeled as '''Takakurayama'''.
At the summit of Hiwashiyama, there is an ancient Kofun known as '''{{ill|Takakurayama Kofun (Ise)|ja|高倉山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}''', a '''circular Kofun (円墳, enpun)'''. Other ancient Kofuns are also believed to exist within the area. Historically, the mountain was called '''Takakasayama''' or '''Takazasayama''', but due to a misreading of "坐" as "Kura," it became known as '''Takakurayama'''.
Takakurayama was historically designated as a '''sacred forest (御杣山, Misomayama)''', supplying timber for the '''{{ill|Shikinen Sengu|ja|神宮式年遷宮|12=draft|12=draft}}''' rebuilding rituals. However, due to the depletion of '''Japanese cypress (ヒノキ, Hinoki)''', the '''official timber source changed multiple times''' until finally settling in the '''Kiso Valley'''.
Since the late '''Taishō period''', '''reforestation projects''' began on '''Takakurayama''', along with '''{{ill|Kaminomichi-yama|ja|神路山|12=draft|12=draft}}''' and '''{{ill|Shimonomichi-yama|ja|島路山|12=draft|12=draft}}'''. These forests are expected to be mature enough for '''use in the shrine rebuilding ceremonies by the year 2125'''. To protect the forest, '''entry to Takakurayama has been prohibited since the late Shōwa era (1970s)'''.
== Takakurayama Kofun == {{see also|{{ill|Takakurayama Kofun (Ise)|ja|高倉山古墳_(伊勢市)|12=draft|12=draft}}}} {{right|[[File:Takakura-yama(Ise)_03.JPG|thumb|250px|{{ill|Takakurayama Kofun (Ise)|ja|高倉山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}]]}} Takakurayama Kofun is a '''late Kofun period circular Kofun''' (円墳, enpun) with a '''diameter of 32 meters and a height of 8 meters'''. However, it features an '''unusually large stone chamber (横穴式石室, yokoana-shiki sekishitsu)''', measuring '''18.5 meters in total length and 4.1 meters in height''', which is disproportionate to the size of the mound.
The '''burial chamber (玄室, genshitsu)''' itself is '''9.7 meters long, 3.3 meters wide, and 4.1 meters high'''. Evidence suggests it was '''looted during the Kamakura period'''.
Since the mound is located '''within the precincts of Ise Grand Shrine''', it was '''worshipped as Ama-no-Iwato (天岩戸, the "Heavenly Rock Cave")''' from the '''late Muromachi to the late Edo period'''. However, due to the '''ban on entry to Takakurayama''', it is no longer accessible to visitors.
Initially, the kofun was believed to have been built in the '''7th century''', but '''excavations in 1975''' revealed that it was '''constructed in the mid-6th century'''. The excavation uncovered artifacts such as: * '''{{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|12=draft|12=draft}} (Sueki pottery)''' * '''{{ill|Haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|12=draft|12=draft}} (Haji pottery)''' * '''{{ill|Horse trappings|ja|馬具|12=draft|12=draft}}''' * '''{{ill|Tachi|ja|鉄刀|12=draft|12=draft}} (Iron swords)''' * '''{{ill|Kozuka|ja|刀子|12=draft|12=draft}} (Small knives)''' * '''Various beads (玉類, gyokurui)'''
== Related Topics == * {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|List of kofun in Japan|ja|日本の古墳一覧|12=draft|12=draft}}
== External Links == * [https://www.city.ise.mie.jp/cul_spo_edu/culture/bunkazai_shiseki/bunkazai/kinenbutsu/1005935.html Takakurayama Kofun – Ise City, Mie Prefecture]
